Multi-Channel Outreach: Meeting Buyers Where They Are
Account-based sales development is not a single-channel strategy. In 2026, B2B buyers interact with brands across a range of channels before they ever speak to a sales representative. Your ABSD program needs to meet them at every touchpoint.

Email: Still the backbone of SDR outreach, but it must be exceptional. Subject lines that stand out. Body copy that gets to the point in three sentences. A clear, low-friction call to action. Email sequences for Tier One accounts should be crafted individually, not templated.

LinkedIn: In 2026, LinkedIn has become the primary hunting ground for B2B sales development. Connection requests, InMail, content engagement, and commenting on prospects' posts are all legitimate touchpoints. Social selling is a real skill, and the best SDRs on LinkedIn are not just sending connection requests — they are building genuine presence and authority in their target vertical.

Phone: Cold calling is not dead. It is evolving. In account-based sales, calls are not cold — they are warm because you have done your research. A well-timed call to a Tier One account, preceded by two or three digital touchpoints, consistently outperforms mass cold calling programs.

Content Syndication: One of the most underutilized levers in ABSD is content syndication. Placing your company's thought leadership content — whitepapers, reports, webinars — in front of your target accounts through third-party distribution networks generates awareness and intent signals simultaneously. When a contact at one of your target accounts downloads your content, that is a powerful signal to your SDR team.

Paid Advertising: Account-based advertising — showing display or social ads exclusively to contacts within your Target Account List — is a powerful complement to direct outreach. It keeps your brand top of mind, reinforces your SDR's messaging, and shortens sales cycles.

The most effective ABSD programs run coordinated plays across all these channels simultaneously, creating a surrounding experience for target accounts that feels inevitable.

Sales and Marketing Alignment: The Non-Negotiable Requirement
Account-based sales development does not work if sales and marketing are operating from different playbooks. Alignment between these two functions is the single biggest organizational predictor of ABSD success.

What does alignment look like in practice?

It starts with a shared definition of the Ideal Customer Profile and Target Account List. Marketing should not be generating leads that sales ignores, and sales should not be pursuing accounts that marketing has no context on. Both teams need to agree on which accounts matter, why they matter, and what success looks like.

It extends to shared metrics. Traditional funnel metrics — MQLs generated, leads passed to sales — are insufficient in an account-based model. Modern revenue teams track account engagement scores, pipeline coverage from target accounts, deal velocity within the TAL, and win rates on target accounts versus non-target accounts.

It requires a shared technology layer. Your CRM, marketing automation platform, intent data provider, and sales engagement tool need to be integrated so that every interaction — whether it originates in marketing or sales — is visible to the entire revenue team. In 2026, revenue operations (RevOps) has become the organizational function that makes this possible, and companies with mature RevOps functions consistently outperform those without.

Intent Data: The Supercharger for Modern ABSD Programs
Intent data is the technology development that has most dramatically changed account-based sales development in recent years. Understanding it — and using it well — is now a core competency for any serious B2B revenue team.

Intent data is behavioral data that signals a company's interest in a particular topic, solution, or category. It is collected from across the web — content consumption, search activity, social engagement, review site visits — and aggregated by intent data providers into signals that your sales and marketing team can act on.

There are two types of intent data:

First-Party Intent: Behavioral signals generated on your own properties — website visits, content downloads, email engagement, product usage. This is the highest-quality intent data available to you, and capturing and activating it should be a priority.

Third-Party Intent: Behavioral signals collected across publisher networks, content syndication platforms, and review sites outside your own properties. This gives you visibility into accounts that are in a buying journey even before they have visited your website.

In an ABSD context, intent data serves several critical functions. It helps you prioritize your Target Account List — surfacing accounts that are showing active buying signals so your SDRs know where to focus. It informs your personalization — if you know an account has been consuming content about data security compliance, your outreach can lead with that specific pain point. And it helps you time your outreach — reaching out to an account when they are actively researching is dramatically more effective than reaching out at a random time.

